name: Wholesale access
description: Purported access to a network, resource or service by means of compromised access credentials, exploitation of a software vulnerability or misconfiguration or via similar means for which no indicator exists that a threat actor verified the validity of access as operational.

name: Chatbot abuse
description: The malicious use of a software application that simulates and processes human conversation. An example includes the ChatGPT bot, which could be used to draft phishing emails or create code.

name: Artificial intelligence (AI) fraud
description: The malicious use of AI technology to facilitate deception or persuasion, typically for social engineering. AI can allow actors to mimic human activity, automate elements of an attack or bypass verification processes and defenses.

name: Deepfake technology
description: Realistic looking and/or sounding artificial video, images and audio that can be used for impersonation, document forgery, BEC attacks, etc.

name: GIR 4.6 CoA
description: Identify and characterize products, tools, services and methods used to weaponize AI against my organization, industry or supply chain.

name: GIR 4.6 CoA
description: Determine capability and intent of adversaries leveraging AI for malicious purposes.
The various types of malicious software used to disrupt, damage or gain unauthorized access to a computer system.
Ransomware is malicious software that threatens to publish the victim's data or perpetually block access to it unless a ransom is paid.
ATM malware is designed to steal financial information and/or cash from ATMs by exploiting vulnerabilities in the machine�s hardware or software.
IoT malware is a type of trojan used to compromise networked devices for nefarious purposes such as forming botnets to launch network attacks.
DoS malware is a type of trojan used to conduct denial of service attacks.
Proxy malware is a type of trojan used to turn an infected computer system into a proxy server from which an attacker can stage nefarious activities anonymously.
Destructive malware is a type of trojan used to destroy or delete files on a computer system or network.
Cryptocurrency mining (cryptomining) or cryptojacking malware is designed to use a device�s CPU resources to mine cryptocurrency without authorization.
Mobile malware is malicious software designed to compromise devices such as phones, smartwatches and tablets to steal sensitive financial and personal information and to gain remote access.
Remote access trojan (RAT) malware is malicious software designed to allow attackers to monitor and control a computer system or network remotely.
Banking trojan malware is designed to steal account-related information related to card payments, online banking and e-payment gateways.
Information-stealer (or info stealer) malware is designed to gather information from a system such as login credentials, keystrokes and screenshots of sensitive information.
Loader malware is designed to download and/or drop malicious payload code onto an infected computer system.

Botnet malware is a type of trojan used to form a botnet (a collection of internet-connected devices, known as bots, that are commanded and controlled by malicious actors to carry out nefarious activities).
Worm malware is a self-replicating, standalone software program designed to spread throughout a network without human assistance.
PoS malware is designed to steal information related to financial transactions such as payment card data from compromised PoS devices.
MaaS is the lease of software or hardware for developing, testing and/or distributing malware.
Services leased to offer multifunctional malware with various functionalities.
Services typically sold or leased under an affiliate program to other actors for launching ransomware attacks and sharing profits.
The various tools, delivery methods and providers used to enable, distribute and execute malware attacks.
Services provided to client actors for distributing, installing and executing malware onto a number of target hosts either directly or through a third-party affiliate.
Automated threats that utilize compromised websites to divert web traffic, scan for vulnerable browser-based applications and run malware.

The abuse of open and closed source tools and software normally used for legitimate administrative or security functions such as penetration testing, domain administration, network and vulnerability scanning, etc.
Frameworks used to manage hosts after initial access, fingerprint vulnerable hosts and exploit them. Examples include Cobalt Strike, Core Impact, Immunity Canvas, Metasploit and PowerShell Empire.
Tools that enumerate hosts on a network and probe them for vulnerabilities or information. Examples include Nessus, Nmap and custom tools.
Tools that can steal passwords from a host. Examples include LaZagne and Mimikatz.
Tools to gather information about or exploit an Active Directory server. Examples include AdFind and BloodHound.
Tools to manipulate a system remotely over the network. Examples include LogMeIn, PuTTY and TeamViewer.
The process of improving website traffic and ranking on search engines. Abuse includes blackhat techniques such as poisoning, keyword stuffing, cloaking and doorway pages.

Software that aids anonymity by masking or concealing digital fingerprints. The most common example is anti-detect browsers, which mimic popular web browsers to provide complete confidentiality and evade detection.
The use of online advertising to spread malware typically involving injecting malicious or malware-laden advertisements into legitimate online advertising networks and webpages.
The list of human-readable instructions that a programmer writes to develop a malware program.

Modules or packages used in financial malware that typically inject hypertext markup language (HTML) or JavaScript code into content before it�s rendered on a web browser, altering what the unsuspecting user sees on the browser, as opposed to what�s actually sent by the server.
An advanced type of web-inject that automatically initiates fund transfers from an infected victim account and conceals funds stolen.
Fully undetectable (FUD) malicious code that has been encrypted, making it more difficult for anti-virus signature detection.
CAV services enable the semiautomated and clandestine development of malware, maximizing the malware�s impact when deployed in the wild.
Stolen digital certificates actors use to sign malicious software or impersonate legitimate websites.
Stolen digital certificates actors use to sign malicious software to evade detection.
Stolen digital certificates actors use to create illegitimate websites for nefarious purposes, typically by impersonating legitimate banking, e-commerce and social networking websites.
Unsolicited email, short message service (SMS) and other types of messages used to deliver malware or malspam.
Services that buy and sell web traffic to direct web users from one website to another, typically to distribute malware.
A service model that delivers computer infrastructure - solely dedicated for criminal use or otherwise legitimate but compromised - on an outsourced basis to support criminal operations.
Hosting services that are lenient about the kinds of activity and material they allow their customers to upload and distribute and generally are immune to law enforcement or takedown efforts.
Services offering leased infrastructure, typically residential consumer IP addresses, as proxy servers to anonymize illicit communications and obfuscate the true origin of nefarious clients.
Services offering private and anonymous domain registration on behalf of nefarious clients.
Services offering botnets for lease, typically to conduct spamming, phishing, distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks and/or credential theft.
Infrastructure belonging to legitimate individual or business entities that is repurposed for malicious activity.
Infrastructure intended for malicious activity and not attributed to IaaS offerings or compromised or abused legitimate systems.

The process, typically at the final stage of a fraudulent scheme, of transferring illicit proceeds to a threat actor or designated representative. Common methods include ATM withdrawals, purchasing digital currencies, transferring funds to online payment platforms or buying goods or gift cards.
Schemes to manufacture, counterfeit, alter, sell and/or use identity documents and other fraudulent documents. Also known as identity fraud.
Schemes involving the creation or registration of new fictitious accounts using stolen personally identifiable information (PII).
Schemes involving the fraudulent purchase, typically using stolen payment cards, and delivery of items from an online merchant to a reshipper to resell on the black market.

The scammer impersonates a legitimate employee and sends an email to payroll or human resources (HR) personnel who is tricked into updating the employee's payroll records with the scammer's bank account and routing number, leading to further fraudulent payroll deposits and payments. The scheme involves social engineering, phishing and business email compromise(BEC)/email account compromise (EAC)/business email spoofing (BES).
The act of defrauding a retail store via the return process. Types include did not arrive (DNA), empty box (EB) or partially empty box (PEB), and fake tracking ID (FTID).
A fraudulent scheme involving layering, transferring or changing the form of money through complex transactions to obscure the origin and/or destination of illicit funds.
The misuse of legitimate or nefarious exchanges and services for money laundering purposes, bypassing fraud controls to cash out criminally obtained funds.
Mules are people who wittingly or unwittingly were recruited to launder stolen money or goods for criminals or criminal organizations.
Refers to threat actor-controlled or compromised victim accounts, typically online banking or e-commerce, used for receiving illicit funds for cashout or laundering purposes.
The abuse, compromise or tampering of legitimate prepaid or gift cards for fraudulent purposes.

The abuse of legitimate services such as airlines and car-sharing rides (shuttles or ride-hailing such as Uber or Lyft) via compromised travel rewards points, membership accounts or fraudulent travel documents.
The abuse of legitimate hotel and accommodation services via compromised loyalty accounts or fraudulent documents.
Schemes typically employed during tax season involving deceiving or tricking victims into unwittingly disclosing credentials, money and personally identifiable information (PII).
A type of scam that relies heavily on social engineering tactics to trick unsuspecting employees and executives into executing fraudulent wire transfer payments.
The collection, utilization and sale of data to facilitate or enable malicious activity.

(also known as "carding") Credit or debit card information obtained, sold or used by unauthorized individuals. Card verification value (CVV) is underground jargon for a stolen credit card consisting of data that only can be used with online retailers (also known as "card not present" fraud). "Fullz" refers to financial information associated with stolen credit cards that includes more than standard account information including Social Security number, date of birth and more. "Dump" is underground jargon for stolen credit card data that can be encoded onto a physical plastic card and used for instore purchases (also known as "card present" fraud).
A form of payment card fraud whereby a payment page on a website is compromised using a malicious script.
The unlawful exposure, sale or unauthorized use of legitimate user account authentication information - typically username and password - that has been stolen for malicious purposes.
(also known as �combo list�) Refers to a usually long text file containing compromised credential pairs that is used in account-checking tools to check validity of credentials against login forms.

The unlawful exposure, sale or unauthorized use of any data that potentially could be used to identify a particular person. Examples include a full name, Social Security number, driver's license number, bank account number, passport number and email address.

(also known as personal health information) The unlawful exposure, sale or unauthorized use of any health data that could potentially be used to identify a particular person. Examples include a full name, medical record number, health insurance information and certificate or license number.
The unlawful exposure, sale or unauthorized use of copyrights, patents, trademarks, trade secrets or any product of the human intellect that the law protects from unauthorized use by others.
The exposure or sale of unlawful or unauthorized access to a network or system.
The exposure or sale of unlawful or unauthorized access to a network or system hosted by a cloud service provider.
The unlawful exposure, sale or unauthorized use of sensitive information used for business operations such as internal-only documents, financial statements, emails and employee information.
A form of identity theft in which the fraudster gets access to a victim's bank or credit card accounts � through a data breach, malware or phishing � and uses them to make unauthorized transactions.
A service that allows scammers to hire multilingual men and women to defeat phone-based anti-fraud measures using social engineering techniques.
A credential-based attack used to test the validity of compromised credentials against login forms.
Text configuration files developed for use in account-checking tools to target specific organizations using combination lists.
A credential attack method used to crack the username and password of accounts through trial and error.
A type of brute-force attack in which a malicious actor uses a single password against targeted user accounts before moving on to attempt a second password, and so on.

(also known as port-out scam, SIM splitting and simjacking) A type of account takeover fraud that targets a weakness in short message service (SMS)-based two-factor authentication (2FA) and two-step verification by tricking a target�s mobile carrier into transferring someone�s wireless service to a device controlled by an illicit actor.
The fraudulent practice of masquerading as a legitimate or reputable entity to trick a victim into revealing personal information, such as passwords or payment card details.
The fraudulent practice of sending emails ostensibly from a known or trusted sender to induce targeted individuals to reveal confidential information.

The fraudulent practice of making phone calls or leaving voice messages purporting to be from reputable companies to induce individuals to reveal personal information, such as bank details and credit card numbers.
The fraudulent practice of tricking social media users into revealing sensitive personal data or sending money. Types include romance scams, sextortion, imposter scams and more.
(also known as (short message service) SMS phishing) The fraudulent practice of tricking a user into revealing sensitive personal data or sending money via a text or SMS message.
(also known as telephone-oriented attack delivery (TOAD)) The fraudulent practice of combining phishing emails and underground call services to trick victims into providing access to their systems.

The circumvention of security measures and techniques designed to limit access to a system or resource. Multifactor authentication (MFA) codes and one-time passwords (OTPs) typically are stolen from users via social engineering, giving threat actors access to private accounts.

The fraudulent practice of circumventing MFA authentication on an account to gain unauthorized access to data. Techniques include brute-forcing the two-factor authentication (2FA) process or the use of social engineering to trick users into approving a fraudulent access request.

A type of MFA bypass where threat actors intercept an OTP, typically sent via SMS, email or a mobile authentication application, to gain unauthorized access to an account. Techniques include SIM card swaps, brute-forcing, social engineering or the use of OTP bypass bots.
Identifying critical technical, personnel and organizational elements of intelligence an adversary would need about a target to best attack. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

Developing and/or acquiring the software, data and techniques used at different phases of an operation. This is the process of identifying development requirements and implementing solutions such as malware, delivery mechanisms, obfuscation and cryptographic protections, and call back and operations and maintenance (O&M) functions. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

Techniques that use entry vectors to gain an initial foothold within a network. Techniques used to gain a foothold include targeted spear-phishing and exploiting weaknesses on public-facing web servers. Footholds gained through initial access may allow for continued access, such as valid accounts and use of external remote services, or may be of limited use due to changing passwords. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

Techniques adversaries may use to communicate with systems under their control within a victim network. Adversaries commonly attempt to mimic normal, expected traffic to avoid detection. There are many ways an adversary can establish command and control with various levels of stealth depending on the victim�s network structure and defenses. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

Techniques adversaries may use to steal data from a network. Once they�ve collected data, adversaries often package it to avoid detection while removing it. This can include compression and encryption. Techniques to exfiltrate data out of a target network typically include transferring it over their command and control channel or an alternate channel and may also include putting size limits on the transmission. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

Techniques adversaries use to disrupt availability or compromise integrity by manipulating business and operational processes. Techniques used for impact can include destroying or tampering with data. In some cases, business processes can look fine, but may have been altered to benefit the adversaries� goals. Adversaries might use these techniques to follow through on their end goal or to provide cover for a confidentiality breach. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

Adversaries may modify visual content available internally or externally to an enterprise network. Reasons for defacement include delivering messaging, intimidation or claiming real or false credit for an intrusion. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

Adversaries may perform network denial of service (DoS) attacks to degrade or block the availability of targeted resources to users. Network DoS attacks can be performed by exhausting the network bandwidth services use. Example resources include specific websites, email services, domain name system (DNS) and web-based applications. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

Techniques that result in adversary-controlled code running on a local or remote system. Techniques that run malicious code often are paired with techniques from all other tactics to achieve broader goals, such as exploring a network or stealing data. For example, an adversary might use a remote access tool to run a PowerShell script that does remote system discovery. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

Techniques adversaries use to keep access to systems across restarts, changed credentials and other interruptions that could cut off their access. Techniques used for persistence include any access, action or configuration changes that let them maintain their foothold on systems, such as replacing or hijacking legitimate code or adding startup code. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

Techniques adversaries use to gain higher-level permissions on a system or network. Adversaries often can enter and explore a network with unprivileged access but require elevated permissions to follow through on their objectives. Common approaches are to take advantage of system weaknesses, misconfigurations and vulnerabilities. Examples of elevated access include: SYSTEM or root level, local administrator, user account with administrator-like access and user accounts with access to specific systems or which perform specific functions. These techniques often overlap with persistence techniques, as OS features that let an adversary persist can execute in an elevated context. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

Techniques adversaries use to avoid detection throughout their compromise. Techniques used for defense evasion include uninstalling or disabling security software or obfuscating and encrypting data and scripts. Adversaries also can leverage and abuse trusted processes to hide and masquerade their malware. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

Techniques used to steal credentials like account names and passwords. Techniques used to obtain credentials include keylogging or credential dumping. Using legitimate credentials can give adversaries access to systems, make them harder to detect and provide the opportunity to create more accounts to help achieve their goals. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

Techniques an adversary may use to gain knowledge about the system and internal network. These techniques help adversaries observe the environment and orient themselves before deciding how to act. They also allow adversaries to explore what they can control and what�s around their entry point to discover how it could benefit their current objective. Native operating system tools are often used toward this post-compromise information-gathering objective. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

Techniques adversaries use to enter and control remote systems on a network. Following through on their primary objective often requires exploring the network to find their target and subsequently gain access to it. Reaching their objective often involves pivoting through multiple systems and accounts to gain access. Adversaries might install their own remote access tools to accomplish lateral movement or use legitimate credentials with native network and operating system tools, which may be stealthier. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

Techniques adversaries may use to gather information that is relevant to following through on the adversary's objectives. Frequently, the next goal after collecting data is to steal or exfiltrate the data. Common target sources include various drive types, browsers, audio, video and email. Common collection methods include capturing screenshots and keyboard input. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

Seeks to exploit an organization through a less secure third-party element in its supply chain. These attacks often are successful since they typically exploit legitimate services to conceal their activity. Supply chain attacks also only require one exploit but likely will open up multiple attack vectors to other organizations.
Gaining unauthorized access to a computer system or network for politically or socially motivated purposes.

Commonly known as �true nonprofits� by those who work in the industry, a charitable organization receives IRS tax exemption status and is funded primarily through charitable donations and government grants. Examples include churches, hospitals dedicated to medical research and government units involved in charitable causes.

Organizations that promote philanthropy and positive change through their work and mission. They are allowed to freely participate in lobbying efforts that might help pass or repeal legislation. They are also allowed to publicly endorse and promote legislation to gain support. Examples include the American Association of Retired Persons (AARP), the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU), health maintenance organizations (HMOs) and Rotary clubs.

An NGO is a nonprofit, citizen-based group that functions independently of a government. Sometimes called civil societies, NGOs are organized on community, national and international levels to serve specific social or political purposes and are cooperative, rather than commercial, in nature. Examples include The American Red Cross, the World Wildlife Fund and Oxfam.

A private charitable foundation is a privately owned nonprofit established to address global concerns such as education, medical research, environmental issues and more. Private charitable foundations are normally established by a single wealthy benefactor or business and are used to grant money to smaller, more niche nonprofits. Examples include the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation and the Coca-Cola Foundation Inc.

Social advocacy groups primarily focus on lobbying and promoting social or political change and are proactively involved in legislation for advancing change. Social advocacy groups rely heavily on membership dues to help supplement the money they receive from public donations. Examples include the Electronic Frontier Foundation, the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP), the National Rifle Association (NRA) and the World Economic Forum.

name: 4 - Fraud, Identity Theft and Unauthorized Access
description: The enablement and facilitation for abuse and monetization of people, processes and technologies.

name: Cashout
description: The process, typically at the final stage of a fraudulent scheme, of transferring illicit proceeds to a threat actor or designated representative. Common methods include ATM withdrawals, purchasing digital currencies, transferring funds to online payment platforms or buying goods or gift cards.

name: Document fraud
description: Schemes to manufacture, counterfeit, alter, sell and/or use identity documents and other fraudulent documents. Also known as identity fraud.

name: Registration fraud
description: Schemes involving the creation or registration of new fictitious accounts using stolen personally identifiable information (PII).

name: Reshipping fraud
description: Schemes involving the fraudulent purchase, typically using stolen payment cards, and delivery of items from an online merchant to a reshipper to resell on the black market.

name: Payroll fraud scam
description: The scammer impersonates a legitimate employee and sends an email to payroll or human resources (HR) personnel who is tricked into updating the employee's payroll records with the scammer's bank account and routing number, leading to further fraudulent payroll deposits and payments. The scheme involves social engineering, phishing and business email compromise(BEC)/email account compromise (EAC)/business email spoofing (BES).

name: Refund fraud
description: The act of defrauding a retail store via the return process. Types include did not arrive (DNA), empty box (EB) or partially empty box (PEB), and fake tracking ID (FTID).

name: Money laundering
description: A fraudulent scheme involving layering, transferring or changing the form of money through complex transactions to obscure the origin and/or destination of illicit funds.

name: Cryptocurrency exchange fraud
description: The misuse of legitimate or nefarious exchanges and services for money laundering purposes, bypassing fraud controls to cash out criminally obtained funds.

name: Mules and networks
description: Mules are people who wittingly or unwittingly were recruited to launder stolen money or goods for criminals or criminal organizations.

name: Drop accounts and fund transfers
description: Refers to threat actor-controlled or compromised victim accounts, typically online banking or e-commerce, used for receiving illicit funds for cashout or laundering purposes.

name: Prepaid or gift card fraud
description: The abuse, compromise or tampering of legitimate prepaid or gift cards for fraudulent purposes.

name: Travel fraud
description: The abuse of legitimate services such as airlines and car-sharing rides (shuttles or ride-hailing such as Uber or Lyft) via compromised travel rewards points, membership accounts or fraudulent travel documents.

name: Hospitality fraud
description: The abuse of legitimate hotel and accommodation services via compromised loyalty accounts or fraudulent documents.

name: Tax fraud and scams
description: Schemes typically employed during tax season involving deceiving or tricking victims into unwittingly disclosing credentials, money and personally identifiable information (PII).

name: Business email compromise (BEC)
description: A type of scam that relies heavily on social engineering tactics to trick unsuspecting employees and executives into executing fraudulent wire transfer payments.

name: Compromised data or access
description: The collection, utilization and sale of data to facilitate or enable malicious activity.

name: Payment card fraud
description: (also known as "carding") Credit or debit card information obtained, sold or used by unauthorized individuals. Card verification value (CVV) is underground jargon for a stolen credit card consisting of data that only can be used with online retailers (also known as "card not present" fraud). "Fullz" refers to financial information associated with stolen credit cards that includes more than standard account information including Social Security number, date of birth and more. "Dump" is underground jargon for stolen credit card data that can be encoded onto a physical plastic card and used for instore purchases (also known as "card present" fraud).

name: Online payment card skimming
description: A form of payment card fraud whereby a payment page on a website is compromised using a malicious script.

name: Compromised credentials
description: The unlawful exposure, sale or unauthorized use of legitimate user account authentication information - typically username and password - that has been stolen for malicious purposes.

name: Credential combination list(s)
description: (also known as �combo list�) Refers to a usually long text file containing compromised credential pairs that is used in account-checking tools to check validity of credentials against login forms.

name: Compromised personally identifiable information (PII)
description: The unlawful exposure, sale or unauthorized use of any data that potentially could be used to identify a particular person. Examples include a full name, Social Security number, driver's license number, bank account number, passport number and email address.

name: Compromised protected health information (PHI)
description: (also known as personal health information) The unlawful exposure, sale or unauthorized use of any health data that could potentially be used to identify a particular person. Examples include a full name, medical record number, health insurance information and certificate or license number.

name: Compromised intellectual property (IP)
description: The unlawful exposure, sale or unauthorized use of copyrights, patents, trademarks, trade secrets or any product of the human intellect that the law protects from unauthorized use by others.

name: Compromised network or system access
description: The exposure or sale of unlawful or unauthorized access to a network or system.

name: Compromised cloud service provider access
description: The exposure or sale of unlawful or unauthorized access to a network or system hosted by a cloud service provider.

name: Compromised business intelligence
description: The unlawful exposure, sale or unauthorized use of sensitive information used for business operations such as internal-only documents, financial statements, emails and employee information.

name: Account takeover (ATO)
description: A form of identity theft in which the fraudster gets access to a victim's bank or credit card accounts � through a data breach, malware or phishing � and uses them to make unauthorized transactions.

name: Call centers
description: A service that allows scammers to hire multilingual men and women to defeat phone-based anti-fraud measures using social engineering techniques.

name: Account checking and credential stuffing
description: A credential-based attack used to test the validity of compromised credentials against login forms.

name: Account-checking configuration file(s)
description: Text configuration files developed for use in account-checking tools to target specific organizations using combination lists.

name: Account brute forcing
description: A credential attack method used to crack the username and password of accounts through trial and error.

name: Password spraying
description: A type of brute-force attack in which a malicious actor uses a single password against targeted user accounts before moving on to attempt a second password, and so on.

name: Subscriber identity module (SIM) swapping
description: (also known as port-out scam, SIM splitting and simjacking) A type of account takeover fraud that targets a weakness in short message service (SMS)-based two-factor authentication (2FA) and two-step verification by tricking a target�s mobile carrier into transferring someone�s wireless service to a device controlled by an illicit actor.

name: Phishing
description: The fraudulent practice of masquerading as a legitimate or reputable entity to trick a victim into revealing personal information, such as passwords or payment card details.

name: Spear-phishing
description: The fraudulent practice of sending emails ostensibly from a known or trusted sender to induce targeted individuals to reveal confidential information.

name: Vishing
description: The fraudulent practice of making phone calls or leaving voice messages purporting to be from reputable companies to induce individuals to reveal personal information, such as bank details and credit card numbers.

name: Social media scams
description: The fraudulent practice of tricking social media users into revealing sensitive personal data or sending money. Types include romance scams, sextortion, imposter scams and more.

name: Smishing
description: (also known as (short message service) SMS phishing) The fraudulent practice of tricking a user into revealing sensitive personal data or sending money via a text or SMS message.

name: Callback phishing
description: (also known as telephone-oriented attack delivery (TOAD)) The fraudulent practice of combining phishing emails and underground call services to trick victims into providing access to their systems.

name: Access control bypass
description: The circumvention of security measures and techniques designed to limit access to a system or resource. Multifactor authentication (MFA) codes and one-time passwords (OTPs) typically are stolen from users via social engineering, giving threat actors access to private accounts.

name: Multifactor authentication (MFA) bypass
description: The fraudulent practice of circumventing MFA authentication on an account to gain unauthorized access to data. Techniques include brute-forcing the two-factor authentication (2FA) process or the use of social engineering to trick users into approving a fraudulent access request.

name: One-time password (OTP) bypass
description: A type of MFA bypass where threat actors intercept an OTP, typically sent via SMS, email or a mobile authentication application, to gain unauthorized access to an account. Techniques include SIM card swaps, brute-forcing, social engineering or the use of OTP bypass bots.

name: Reconnaissance and information gathering tactic
description: Identifying critical technical, personnel and organizational elements of intelligence an adversary would need about a target to best attack. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

name: Build capabilities tactic
description: Developing and/or acquiring the software, data and techniques used at different phases of an operation. This is the process of identifying development requirements and implementing solutions such as malware, delivery mechanisms, obfuscation and cryptographic protections, and call back and operations and maintenance (O&M) functions. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

name: Initial access tactic
description: Techniques that use entry vectors to gain an initial foothold within a network. Techniques used to gain a foothold include targeted spear-phishing and exploiting weaknesses on public-facing web servers. Footholds gained through initial access may allow for continued access, such as valid accounts and use of external remote services, or may be of limited use due to changing passwords. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

name: Command and control tactic
description: Techniques adversaries may use to communicate with systems under their control within a victim network. Adversaries commonly attempt to mimic normal, expected traffic to avoid detection. There are many ways an adversary can establish command and control with various levels of stealth depending on the victim�s network structure and defenses. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

name: Exfiltration tactic
description: Techniques adversaries may use to steal data from a network. Once they�ve collected data, adversaries often package it to avoid detection while removing it. This can include compression and encryption. Techniques to exfiltrate data out of a target network typically include transferring it over their command and control channel or an alternate channel and may also include putting size limits on the transmission. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

name: Impact tactic
description: Techniques adversaries use to disrupt availability or compromise integrity by manipulating business and operational processes. Techniques used for impact can include destroying or tampering with data. In some cases, business processes can look fine, but may have been altered to benefit the adversaries� goals. Adversaries might use these techniques to follow through on their end goal or to provide cover for a confidentiality breach. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

name: Defacement technique
description: Adversaries may modify visual content available internally or externally to an enterprise network. Reasons for defacement include delivering messaging, intimidation or claiming real or false credit for an intrusion. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

name: Denial of service (DoS) technique
description: Adversaries may perform network denial of service (DoS) attacks to degrade or block the availability of targeted resources to users. Network DoS attacks can be performed by exhausting the network bandwidth services use. Example resources include specific websites, email services, domain name system (DNS) and web-based applications. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

name: Execution tactic
description: Techniques that result in adversary-controlled code running on a local or remote system. Techniques that run malicious code often are paired with techniques from all other tactics to achieve broader goals, such as exploring a network or stealing data. For example, an adversary might use a remote access tool to run a PowerShell script that does remote system discovery. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

name: Persistence tactic
description: Techniques adversaries use to keep access to systems across restarts, changed credentials and other interruptions that could cut off their access. Techniques used for persistence include any access, action or configuration changes that let them maintain their foothold on systems, such as replacing or hijacking legitimate code or adding startup code. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

name: Privilege escalation tactic
description: Techniques adversaries use to gain higher-level permissions on a system or network. Adversaries often can enter and explore a network with unprivileged access but require elevated permissions to follow through on their objectives. Common approaches are to take advantage of system weaknesses, misconfigurations and vulnerabilities. Examples of elevated access include: SYSTEM or root level, local administrator, user account with administrator-like access and user accounts with access to specific systems or which perform specific functions. These techniques often overlap with persistence techniques, as OS features that let an adversary persist can execute in an elevated context. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

name: Defense evasion tactic
description: Techniques adversaries use to avoid detection throughout their compromise. Techniques used for defense evasion include uninstalling or disabling security software or obfuscating and encrypting data and scripts. Adversaries also can leverage and abuse trusted processes to hide and masquerade their malware. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

name: Credential access tactic
description: Techniques used to steal credentials like account names and passwords. Techniques used to obtain credentials include keylogging or credential dumping. Using legitimate credentials can give adversaries access to systems, make them harder to detect and provide the opportunity to create more accounts to help achieve their goals. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

name: Discovery tactic
description: Techniques an adversary may use to gain knowledge about the system and internal network. These techniques help adversaries observe the environment and orient themselves before deciding how to act. They also allow adversaries to explore what they can control and what�s around their entry point to discover how it could benefit their current objective. Native operating system tools are often used toward this post-compromise information-gathering objective. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

name: Lateral movement tactic
description: Techniques adversaries use to enter and control remote systems on a network. Following through on their primary objective often requires exploring the network to find their target and subsequently gain access to it. Reaching their objective often involves pivoting through multiple systems and accounts to gain access. Adversaries might install their own remote access tools to accomplish lateral movement or use legitimate credentials with native network and operating system tools, which may be stealthier. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

name: Collection tactic
description: Techniques adversaries may use to gather information that is relevant to following through on the adversary's objectives. Frequently, the next goal after collecting data is to steal or exfiltrate the data. Common target sources include various drive types, browsers, audio, video and email. Common collection methods include capturing screenshots and keyboard input. (source: Mitre ATT&CK)

name: Supply chain attack tactic
description: Seeks to exploit an organization through a less secure third-party element in its supply chain. These attacks often are successful since they typically exploit legitimate services to conceal their activity. Supply chain attacks also only require one exploit but likely will open up multiple attack vectors to other organizations.

name: Hacktivism
description: Gaining unauthorized access to a computer system or network for politically or socially motivated purposes.

name: Charitable organizations
description: Commonly known as �true nonprofits� by those who work in the industry, a charitable organization receives IRS tax exemption status and is funded primarily through charitable donations and government grants. Examples include churches, hospitals dedicated to medical research and government units involved in charitable causes.

name: Civic leagues and social welfare organizations
description: Organizations that promote philanthropy and positive change through their work and mission. They are allowed to freely participate in lobbying efforts that might help pass or repeal legislation. They are also allowed to publicly endorse and promote legislation to gain support. Examples include the American Association of Retired Persons (AARP), the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU), health maintenance organizations (HMOs) and Rotary clubs.

name: Nongovernmental organizations (NGOs)
description: An NGO is a nonprofit, citizen-based group that functions independently of a government. Sometimes called civil societies, NGOs are organized on community, national and international levels to serve specific social or political purposes and are cooperative, rather than commercial, in nature. Examples include The American Red Cross, the World Wildlife Fund and Oxfam.

name: Private charitable foundations
description: A private charitable foundation is a privately owned nonprofit established to address global concerns such as education, medical research, environmental issues and more. Private charitable foundations are normally established by a single wealthy benefactor or business and are used to grant money to smaller, more niche nonprofits. Examples include the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation and the Coca-Cola Foundation Inc.

name: Social advocacy groups
description: Social advocacy groups primarily focus on lobbying and promoting social or political change and are proactively involved in legislation for advancing change. Social advocacy groups rely heavily on membership dues to help supplement the money they receive from public donations. Examples include the Electronic Frontier Foundation, the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP), the National Rifle Association (NRA) and the World Economic Forum.

name: Supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) systems
Oil, gas and consumable fuels industry
Agriculture and food and beverage production industry
Life sciences and health care sector
Health care providers and services industry
Pharmaceuticals, biotechnology and life sciences industry
Real estate fund and investor industry
Real estate investment trust (REIT) and property company industry
Real estate management, brokerage and service provider industry

name: Clipper malware
description: Designed to steal cryptocurrency by allowing attackers to replace a victim’s cryptocurrency wallet address in the victim’s clipboard with their own.

name: Access classification
description: Differentiation of purported access to a network, resource or service that provides threat actors the potential to further compromise systems, steal sensitive information, install malware and/or launch additional cyberattacks.

name: Specified access
description: Purported access to a network, resource or service by means of compromised access credentials, exploitation of a software vulnerability or misconfiguration or via similar means for which an indicator exists that a threat actor verified the validity of access as operational.

name: Drainer malware
description: Designed to steal cryptocurrency assets such as tokens, artefacts, wallets, non-fungible tokens (NFTs), etc.
